I. Prerequisites
----------------

  pip install requests

Python 3.7 or later is required.  The readline module is used automatically
if available (standard on Linux/macOS) to enable line-editing in interactive
mode.


II. Credentials
---------------

The simplest way to supply credentials for the included development
installation is to source the env.sh file in the parent directory:

  source ../env.sh

This exports:

  CDSE_SERVER   = https://localhost:8443
  CDSE_USER_ID  = EngineAdmin
  CDSE_ORG_ID   = EngineOrg
  CDSE_ORG_KEY  = 187465950C5F9018D04F91E976CAC1D7FA19CBA5FE26D94038630B18BCBAAAB6
  CDSE_STORAGE  = EngineStorage

All examples below assume these variables are exported.  The flag equivalents
are shown in Section IV for reference.

Never pass the org key on the command line in production — it appears in
shell history and process listings.  Use the CDSE_ORG_KEY variable or
interactive mode instead.


III. Quick start
----------------

  # Source the development credentials
  source ../env.sh

  # Verify the engine is reachable
  python3 cdse_client.py --insecure info

  # Store a file as an encrypted secret
  echo "top secret payload" > /tmp/payload.txt
  python3 cdse_client.py --insecure store-secret demo-secret /tmp/payload.txt

  # Retrieve it
  python3 cdse_client.py --insecure get-secret demo-secret

  # Clean up
  python3 cdse_client.py --insecure delete-secret demo-secret

For HTTP (BYPASSTLSAUTHINHTTP build) replace --insecure with
--server http://localhost:8080.


IV. Command reference
---------------------

Usage:
  python3 cdse_client.py [OPTIONS] COMMAND [ARGS...]

Options:

  --server HOST          CaumeDSE server URL or host:port.
                         Default: $CDSE_SERVER or localhost:8443.
  --user-id USER_ID      userId credential.  Default: $CDSE_USER_ID.
  --org-id ORG_ID        orgId credential.   Default: $CDSE_ORG_ID.
  --org-key ORG_KEY      orgKey (encryption key).  Default: $CDSE_ORG_KEY.
                         Use the env variable or interactive mode to avoid
                         exposure in shell history.
  --storage STORAGE      Storage bucket name.  Default: $CDSE_STORAGE or
                         EngineStorage.
  --ca-cert FILE         Path to a PEM CA certificate for TLS verification.
                         Example: --ca-cert /opt/cdse/ca.pem
  --insecure, -k         Disable TLS certificate verification.
                         Development/local testing only.
  --interactive, -i      Enter interactive REPL mode after credential setup.

Commands:

  info
      Show userId, orgId, role, and storage information for the
      authenticated user.

  list-secrets
      List the names of all encrypted raw-file secrets in the storage.

  store-secret NAME FILE [INFO]
      Upload FILE and store it as an AES-256-GCM encrypted secret named NAME.
      INFO is optional free-text metadata attached to the document.

  get-secret NAME [OUTPUT_FILE]
      Retrieve and decrypt the secret named NAME.  If OUTPUT_FILE is given,
      the decrypted content is written there; otherwise it is printed to
      stdout (binary content is shown as a hex summary).

  delete-secret NAME
      Permanently delete the secret named NAME.

  db-list
      List the names of all encrypted CSV database documents.

  db-create NAME col1,col2,...
      Create a new encrypted CSV database named NAME with the given column
      headers (comma-separated, no spaces around commas).

  db-insert NAME col=val ...
      Append one row to the database NAME.  Each column value is given as a
      col=val pair.  Columns not mentioned are left empty.

  db-query NAME [ROW]
      Print all rows of database NAME as CSV, or print only row number ROW
      (1-based) if specified.

  db-update NAME ROW col=val ...
      Update one or more columns in row ROW of database NAME.

  db-delete-row NAME ROW
      Delete row ROW from database NAME.  Remaining rows are renumbered.

  db-delete NAME
      Delete the entire CSV database document NAME.

  audit-log
      Retrieve the engine's transaction audit log and print it as CSV.
      Each row represents one API request.  Note: field values are encrypted
      in the stored database; this endpoint decrypts them using the orgKey
      before returning.


V. Secrets — full walkthrough
------------------------------

Prepare a test secret file:

  echo "AES-256 master key material" > /tmp/master.key

Store the secret with optional descriptive metadata:

  python3 cdse_client.py --insecure \
      store-secret master-key /tmp/master.key "AES-256 key for prod DB"

Expected output:
  Stored secret 'master-key'.

List all stored secrets:

  python3 cdse_client.py --insecure list-secrets

Expected output (HTML fragment with document ID list):
  <html>...<b>200 OK</b>...master-key...

Retrieve the secret to a file:

  python3 cdse_client.py --insecure \
      get-secret master-key /tmp/master-retrieved.key

Expected output:
  Written to '/tmp/master-retrieved.key'.

Verify the content round-tripped correctly:

  diff /tmp/master.key /tmp/master-retrieved.key

Retrieve to stdout (text content):

  python3 cdse_client.py --insecure get-secret master-key

Expected output:
  AES-256 master key material

Delete the secret:

  python3 cdse_client.py --insecure delete-secret master-key

Expected output:
  Deleted secret 'master-key'.


VI. Encrypted CSV database — full walkthrough
----------------------------------------------

Create the database with column headers:

  python3 cdse_client.py --insecure \
      db-create contacts id,name,email,phone

Expected output:
  Created CSV document 'contacts' with columns: id,name,email,phone

Insert rows (col=val pairs; omitted columns are blank):

  python3 cdse_client.py --insecure \
      db-insert contacts id=1 name=Alice email=alice@example.com phone=555-0100

  python3 cdse_client.py --insecure \
      db-insert contacts id=2 name=Bob email=bob@example.com phone=555-0200

  python3 cdse_client.py --insecure \
      db-insert contacts id=3 name=Carol email=carol@example.com phone=555-0300

Expected output for each insert:
  Inserted row N into 'contacts'.

Query all rows:

  python3 cdse_client.py --insecure db-query contacts

Expected output (CSV):
  id,name,email,phone
  1,Alice,alice@example.com,555-0100
  2,Bob,bob@example.com,555-0200
  3,Carol,carol@example.com,555-0300

Query a specific row (1-based index):

  python3 cdse_client.py --insecure db-query contacts 2

Expected output:
  id,name,email,phone
  2,Bob,bob@example.com,555-0200

Update a column in row 1:

  python3 cdse_client.py --insecure \
      db-update contacts 1 email=alice@newdomain.com phone=555-9999

Expected output:
  Updated row 1 in 'contacts'.

Verify the update:

  python3 cdse_client.py --insecure db-query contacts 1

Expected output:
  id,name,email,phone
  1,Alice,alice@newdomain.com,555-9999

Delete a row:

  python3 cdse_client.py --insecure db-delete-row contacts 3

Expected output:
  Deleted row 3 from 'contacts'.

Delete the entire database:

  python3 cdse_client.py --insecure db-delete contacts

Expected output:
  Deleted CSV document 'contacts'.

List all databases to confirm deletion:

  python3 cdse_client.py --insecure db-list


VII. Interactive mode
---------------------

Start interactive mode; the org key is read without echo:

  python3 cdse_client.py --insecure -i \
      --server https://localhost:8443 \
      --user-id EngineAdmin --org-id EngineOrg

Alternatively, omit --server / --user-id / --org-id and enter them at the
prompts.  The org key prompt always hides input.

At the cdse> prompt, type any command without credentials:

  cdse> info
  cdse> store-secret mykey /tmp/key.bin
  cdse> list-secrets
  cdse> get-secret mykey /tmp/out.bin
  cdse> delete-secret mykey
  cdse> db-create vault id,secret,label
  cdse> db-insert vault id=1 secret=abc123 label=dev
  cdse> db-query vault
  cdse> db-update vault 1 label=production
  cdse> db-delete-row vault 1
  cdse> db-delete vault
  cdse> audit-log
  cdse> help
  cdse> exit

Press Ctrl-D or type exit/quit to leave the session.


VIII. Environment variable reference
--------------------------------------

  CDSE_SERVER    Base URL or host:port of the CDSE instance.
                 Default: localhost:8443
                 Example: https://myserver:8443
                          http://localhost:8080  (BYPASSTLSAUTHINHTTP build)

  CDSE_USER_ID   userId credential.
                 Example: EngineAdmin

  CDSE_ORG_ID    orgId credential.
                 Example: EngineOrg

  CDSE_ORG_KEY   Organisation encryption key.  No default — must be set.
                 Example: 187465950C5F9018D04F91E976CAC1D7FA19CBA5FE26D94038630B18BCBAAAB6
                 (development installation key; see ../env.sh)

  CDSE_STORAGE   Storage bucket name.
                 Default: EngineStorage

Environment variables are overridden by explicit command-line flags.


IX. TLS options
---------------

For the default HTTPS server:

  # Verify the server using the included development CA certificate:
  python3 cdse_client.py --ca-cert /opt/cdse/ca.pem info

  # Disable verification (development only):
  python3 cdse_client.py --insecure info

For the HTTP port (BYPASSTLSAUTHINHTTP build, no TLS):

  python3 cdse_client.py --server http://localhost:8080 info

Never use --insecure or the HTTP port in production.


X. Exit codes
-------------

  0   Success.
  1   Usage error (missing credentials, unknown command) or API error.
